Comment:
Her panic and suffocation made my heart beat hard and relive what happened to me almost 10 years ago: awake paralysis and suffocation during an operation in Brighton in 2005.

First the hospital/anaesthetists said nothing went wrong. Then the consultant anaesthetist (my call to him in desperation) said it was 'awareness' (meaning what's usually called anaesthetic awareness in the UK or unintended intra-operative awareness in the USA). Then this same man at the end of a farcical meeting said I had experienced 'emergence phenomenon' - but decided not to tell me what that was. Then in response to my letter of complaint the Chief exec wrote that nothing went wrong and didn't use any name for what had occurred - supposedly just my abnormal response to normal events. They contacted my GP and told him something but I asked him and he refused to tell me what he had been told. He said at one point 'they didn't know what went wrong' - but of course they must have = a lie.

You'd think (with all their expensive legal expertise paid for by clients/users of their services = us) they'd have created and stuck to one coherent and consistent story wouldn't you?

Yup: suffocation is a terrible way to die and many of us will die in this way. It is utter HELL. I survived it but others have died and will die in hospital because of medical errors by anaesthetists, surgeons, operating department practitioners (ODPs), nurses, recovery room staff etc. A weekend so no senior staff  on-site, agency nurses, poor training for all concerned, arrogance, incompetence, misdiagnosis,not listened to or believed (before and after)...

Can't fix it after (nor my injuries) so it's GOT to be prevention: 'saving' money kills and destroys lives and costs far more in the longterm - but only IF our and our friends' families' lives and health are given their correct value.

Comment:
People comparing Gravity to Interstellar are missing the point entirely.¬† Quite literally an apples-to-oranges comparison fallacy.¬† Just because the two movies are sci fi (and Gravity really is not true SF since it doesn't imagine any technology we don't already have), doesn't make them remotely similar.¬† Interstellar is a relatively sedate *"big-story" sci fi epic*.¬† Gravity is an intimate character portrait coupled with an *action-adventure thriller*.¬† Two very different kinds of movie.¬† Thinking they are somehow comparable, just because both are set in space, is naive.¬†

They're both excellent movies that are very effective at achieving their *very different goals*.  Interstellar's goal is to make you *think*.  Gravity's goal is to make you *care*.

Comment: People keep comparing this to Interstellar but these two films are kind of different. There is a different premise for both films. Try and remember this. The only similarity of both these films is the setting, which is space. And that is all. Gravity, a lady who is trying to return to earth. Interstellar, people that are trying to leave earth. Can't you see? Over all, for a film, I would like to watch what is entertaining, and of that I choose Interstellar. Interesting plot, interesting premise, character development, more emotional instances. If I would like to watch a more down to earth film, which bases more on plot situation more that any other element, then its Gravity. And if you notice, the film is in real-time. Everything happens in almost 90 minutes or so. The film is also more believable and laid back. You just watch what happens. For Interstellar, you have to think in order to get the gist of the movie, and it looks like a handful of people were having trouble with that. But Gravity is missing the awe, the "what if" and imagination, stepping out the comfort zone. So the aim of both films are different. But I'll say this. The film that left me thinking for days after watching it was Interstellar. That's gotta mean something, right?

Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment: I think there are a lot of points to take into consideration , when discussing gravity , not only because it is one of the most highly rated movies of all time , but because it has created such a big division not only among science fiction fanatics but among movie goers in general . Let us get one thing straight . Gravity is a good movie , Is it the best sci_fi I have ever seen ? Absolutely not . did it break the mould ? yeah somehow , but not necessarily because of its presentation or ideas , but more because most of the sci_fi people watch nowadays are so mainstream they mostly worship action , cliches and aliens . gravity in all its essence is really a very simple story about survival . something more akin to cast away than star wars . If gravity was a book , then it would be a short story , not a novel . Back story that is so important in character arcs is not fully exposed on purpose (they could have used flashbacks for example but they didn't) , all you need to know about sandra bullock 's character is that her daughter died , and that she has been living in sorrow ever since .They never fully explored the main character for a few reasons . This is my interpertation of course : Firstly they wanted you to be fully invested in the setting as much as possible , and secondly maybe they thought it would be a tad melodramatic and cliched . Visually speaking , the film is stunning , that every scene so painstakingly crafted is a story in its own . Gravity is not only a simple story favouring symbolism over conventional storytelling but also a visual experience that makes up for its lack of dialogue through prestine , thought provoking imagery that will haunt your dreams for how lonely and dark space can be , yet so beautiful and endless that it would take your breath away . That is why it is so crafty , a single frame can make up for thousands of lines . That is why so many adore this movie . My brother who is a very hard to please kind of person thought it a perfect movie and gave it a 10 . It depends really on your kind of personality . He saw in its simplicity and hauntingly beautiful imagery a story in its own . He loved clooney 's nobelity and liked bulock's fight for survival . But that didn't make it the best movie i ever saw . Yeah the visuals enhanced the atmosphere dramatically and yeah I liked clooney's character . I just never felt for sandra bullock's character . Maybe I demanded more backstory , maybe the role needed a lesser known actress , I just don't know ¬†. Visual imagery was indeed striking but iam one of those people that far favors emotional investment in my stories over gorgeous visual imagery . Simple strorytelling is a double edged sword in movies , and lack in character backstory would have been forgiven if i was emotionaly invested in the fight or if the premise was more original , but neither was the case . But as i said before , gravity is more than the sum of its parts , and I try to understand as much as i can, why people like it so much . It is just that I can't totally adore it or see it as a flawless movie as other people do .

Comment: I have seen a great number of Science Fiction films over the years and read a great many novels. I did not see this in the theater because I knew the scenes would make me dizzy and uncomfortable. I just watched it last night on a large screen TV, and it was over hyped, over rated and no way deserved Oscars except for the SFX. Just as many had observed when it was released it had no plot, no character development, lots of impossible events to swallow, but it was also BORING as hell when there was no explosions or fast flying astronauts to watch, Bullock fiddling with buttons and trying to grab onto parts of the satellites put me to sleep. In the Sci-Fi and Horror genres you have to be able to suspend disbelief when it comes to storyline, you mean to tell me that Dr. Bullock was able to get into a Chinese spacecraft and go 'eny, meny, miny, moe' and pick the right buttons to push to land her safely in the water of earth?¬† 2001 A Space Odyssey it is not, which is why it is being quickly forgotten. Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment:
From the positive reviews of this movie I expected something well researched, deep and subtle. In the end it was just another flashy American movie made for people with short attention spans and a lack of critical thinking skills.

If you know anything about satellites, orbits and space debris you might find it difficult to suspend your disbelief. How likely is it that debris from one destroyed satellite hits the Hubble space telescope, the ISS, several other satellites and a Chinese space station too? Multiple times, over multiple passes.

This movie goes from one suspenseful moment to another, to another, to another, to another and to yet another. After awhile I found myself rolling my eyes every time something went wrong. The suspense was fake and manufactured, I can only pretend to be genuinely concerned for the main character's life so many times before I get desensitized, because who am I kidding, she's not going to die, that'd compromise the feel good moment at the end when she feels reborn and happy to be alive! Can't have that.

Having said that, this movie did genuinely have me tearing up in the quiet moments between the flashy special effects and explosions, only to pull me right back out of the movie again with another moment I'm expected to get all tense over again.

Dialogue is a bit corny too, but I'm not really a person who cares so much about that.

I'd probably give it a 3 or 4 out of 10. If you're not too critical of movies and like allot of suspense in your films, then you'll probably really like this, because in essence it's not a bad film, it's just cheap and pandering, which some people are into.

Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment:
Thought experiment: How a man can traverse space in all directions, even back and forth from distant points, without the need for jet propulsion.
Imagine a man floating in space.¬†
He does not have any type of propulsion system such as a jet-pack or boosters.
He has an umbrella made of Kevlar which is spread open and tethered to his waistline.
The tether is several meters in length, is strength rated for towing, and is fully extended so that a tug on the umbrella will in turn be kinetically transferred to the man, via the tether.
The man has a wrist rocket sling shot strapped to his forearm and wrist that is in prime position for firing.
He has attached to his chest a pouch full of lead ball weights, each weighing about 3 ounces.
The man loads a lead ball into the sling shot and fires it at near full capacity into the concave side of umbrella (now you know why the umbrella is made of Kevlar ;).
The momentum of the travelling lead ball is transferred into the umbrella and the umbrella moves slightly in the same direction the ball had been travelling, thereby causing the man to move in the same direction as well.
As he fires one shot after another into the umbrella, the speed at which he traverses space increases with each shot.
When the man runs out lead balls to fire from his sling shot, he reels in the umbrella- which now retains the entire contents of his ammunition pouch.¬†
After retrieving all of the ammunition from the umbrella and placing each ball back into the ammunition pouch attached to his chest, he can now push the umbrella away from him in any direction he chooses, and can again begin the process of his sling shot powered propulsion system.

Creating the 3D in Gravity.
Gravity, the highly-acclaimed, intensely emotional space thriller, has been hailed as some of the - if not the VERY - best 3D footage ever seen on the big screen. This has led to some surprise when learning that Gravity was NOT shot in 3D. However, it wasn't entirely converted in post either. Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment: Warning: this is an attempt to express my views on the movie. OPINIONS AHEAD! "Meh. It was aight." But seriously, I enjoyed Gravity to an extent. The action scenes were amazing and. . . well. . . that's about it. The cast was a poor choice. Watching Bullock ,(A trained astronaut.), fret for for her life like she did was just dumb. For ANYONE to be qualified to go on a spacewalk, ESPECIALLY to service the Hubble, that person would have had to go through months of training and preparation. Not only training for when it goes right, but when it goes wrong. In fact, a large portion of Astronaut training exercises focus on situations that go wrong, to prepare the astronaut for a dangerous mission. A mission, might I add, you wouldn't be chatting it up during. "WHAT DO I DO WHAT DO I DO?!" is a statement you should NEVER hear from an astronaut, and especially not a space-walker. And I shouldn't even mention the useless "Oh you're running out of air" mechanic that served no purpose. After telling her to breathe lightly, Clooney then proceeds to ask her about her life back on Earth. I call BS. I wouldn't have had a problem in a more Science-fiction movie, but this entire flick is meant to actually happen. And it can. And if they wanted to be accurate, they sure didn't do a good job. I don't feel like pointing out all of the movies flaws. But I must re-state: I did not hate this movie. I just think it was a simple "cash-in" on space to the general audience. The praise this movie is getting is(in my opinion) not deserved. I'm seeing this movie being put on number 1 spots on top 10 Space movies, or some other countdown. The word "Brilliant" is a VERY generous compliment to Gravity. Not to say that it sucked the big one, but definitely not the top of its class. If people are impressed and "deeply moved" by this movie, they are most likely new to the genre. Go watch 2001: A Space Odyssey. LOADS better.

Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment:
So glad im not the only one who thought this movie was¬†garbage!
just another 90 minutes of "avatar" like 3D CGI nonsense with next to no research gone into space travel, physics etc.
Thanks to IMDB user "nysalesman" for the review!¬†
"1) Bullock is nauseous during a space walk. This would never happen. It is only during space walks that space sickness can kill, because vomiting in your enclosed suit would cause you to inhale and choke on the vomit. It is for this reason that food is not consumed for hours prior to an EVA (Extra Vehicular Activity) and astronauts are required to abort the walk when there's even a hint of nausea

2) Bullock is untethered,spinning and flailing in space. This is highly unlikely. NASA procedure is to always have an emergency MMU called a SAFER during EVA. The pack is programmed to automatically adjust yaw, roll, and pitch to stop the astronaut from spinning. Routine procedure is then to manually take control of the jetpack and use it to return to the space vehicle

3) The Soyez TMA re-entry module requires an EVA to disengage the chute. Correct me if I'm wrong, but it is my understanding that this model would allow the astronaut to disengage the chute from within the capsule. BTW, if the chute did deploy, it wouldn't have been opened up and spread all over the station. The parachute compartment hatch would have simply been blown off and the parachute would have remained packed away in the module - there is no wind in space

4) The opening line states that there is no sound in space. However, we hear the wrench actuating when used by Sandra Bullock

5) George Clooney has Bullock on a long tether to distance her from the jets on his jetpack. However, he's holding on to her in front of himself, where she is just as clear of them as he is. Also, the propellent is inert gas, so it would not have hurt her. BTW, Clooney later drifts into space when there is no discernible force to push him away from Bullock

6) The re-entry capsules have a hard 60-second count down before undocking. No way. Design of space vehicles offer manual over-rides for nearly everything. If there were a count down, then there would be an over-ride as well

7) One exploding satellite would not cause a chain reaction of debris. It's called space for a reason, there is a lot of it. Debris from one satellite is highly unlikely to cause further debris

8) Every satellite and space station is bombarded by the debris as if they are all in the same orbit. They are not. For that matter, neither is the Hubble and ISS

9) When Bullock takes off her space suit, there is no liquid cooled ventilation unit, catheter, or diaper: which are required attire for EVA

10) Bullock stabilizes and orients the proper re-entry path of the re-entry module from a spin while well beyond the window for a deorbit burn

11) No way someone with the emotional baggage of Bullock's character would ever be chosen for a space mission

12) Bullock went through astronaut training and wasn't taught to brace herself when using a propellent in zero G

13) The hatch on the Soyez reentry module is much higher and would not have flooded so easily. Additionally, the Soyez, while being designed to land on solid ground, is also designed with floatation devices for water landing and does not have explosive bolts on the hatch. So it would not have flooded like Grissom's Liberty Bell 7"

First, I suspect those ppl didn't watch it in a 3D theater, which is probably the best suited way of watching it. Second, you have to be in the mood for watching it. It's about a POV-experience of being in space and struggling agaist weightlessness. The movie name says it all: it's about gravity (or it's non-existence). Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment:
I know this is a long post, but I feel the need to write it:

I feel compelled to post this message in response to the various amount of hate that Gravity seems to be receiving at the moment, especially on this comment section.¬†

I will stress now that for those of you who didn't like this film, I have no problem with that whatsoever! We all have different tastes and film is subjective at the end of the day. There are going to be films that many people like that you don't and vice versa. We all have different perspectives when it comes to films, so I think it's wrong for people to call you idiots or whatever.¬†

For me personally, I loved Gravity. I saw it in the cinema last November and I loved it. I bought the Blu-Ray yesterday, watched it last night, I loved it. It's my favourite film of 2013.¬†

Why do I love it you may ask? Well, first and foremost, it was because of the experience of being in outer space. Gravity is very much an experience film. A film that you're supposed to immerse yourself in and go in for the ride. On that basis, Gravity delivered that aspect for me. The direction, visuals, music and even the physics portrayed in this film helped that tremendously in my opinion. Just watching the visuals and seeing Sandra Bullock's character overcome the odds stacked against her was intense and absorbing. Because I felt like I was in space with her, I felt her emotions, I felt her loneliness, I felt her need to survive. Also, the end sequence? It gives me chills every time. It is an amazing sequence with the visuals and especially the music. It's a film that's not so much to be watched as it is to be felt and it's also a survival film.¬†

What annoys me about the reaction to this film is how many people just look for the bad things in it and they totally disregard the good stuff. Do we look at all the individual moments we hate or dislike in a film, or do we look at the bigger picture? I think it makes more sense to balance out the good and the bad of a film and see which one holds up more, instead of just focusing on the bad.¬†

One of the complaints people give is that it has no story. I disagree. It is a basic story, but it's still a story! A story about a person in space trying to get back to earth after a disaster takes place. After all, it is a survival film. There's only so much you can do with a premise about a person trying to survive a disaster or an event that arises. I mean, what were people expecting with a film like this? Considering the basic material Alfonson Cuaron had to work with, I thought he did a great job! The film also deals with issues like loneliness, despair, isolation, spirituality, etc, so there's more to this film than people give credit for. I've never seen a survival film done this way before, so Cuaron covered new ground with this film in my opinion.¬†

In terms of the physics, dialogue and cliches in this film? There were maybe a couple of problems, but they never really bothered me that much.¬†

It's in my top ten favourite films of all time and I don't care if people think I'm overrating the film or that I don't have a good taste. I loved the film and nobody will change my enjoyment of this film!¬†

At the end of the day though, if people don't like it because they found it boring or they couldn't get into it, that's totally fine. We all have different opinions and it's a shame that a fair amount of people don't like it, but I wish people wouldn't be as harsh on this film and at least consider the good aspects to it and I believe you can find many. Some people who call it the worst film ever made are just being WAY too critical in my opinion.¬†

If you think I have a bad taste in films, here are my top ten favourite films of all time so you can be the judge:¬†

10. Groundhog Day¬†
9. Inception¬†
8. It‚Äôs a Wonderful Life¬†
7. Brazil¬†
6. Gravity¬†
5. The Lord of the Rings Trilogy¬†
4. The Elephant Man¬†
3. Fantasia¬†
2. Vertigo¬†
1. 2001: A Space Odyssey¬†

I wanted to post this message because I feel that, while people are not wrong for disliking this film, I do believe some people are being a bit too harsh on it in my humble opinion. I mean, why do some people feel the need to be so aggressively negative towards to it? It's just a film at the end of the day. Don't get so worked up over it! and secondly, I wanted to let some of you guys know why me and many others loved this film.

Comment:
The visuals were cool BUT this movie was rife with physical inaccuracies...which really pissed me off because I have a pretty deep understanding of physics. Namely, the scene where George Clooney had to let go - there was no force pulling him away from Sandra Ball-sac to begin with! No gravity, no centripital force.¬† There wouldn't have been any tension on the tether that was holding them. They could have both let go and not moved an inch!
Plus the orbits of the ISS, Hubble, and the Chinese station are so different, there's absolutely no way in hell a NASA jet pack (which was decommissioned years ago) could have gotten two astronauts from one to the other!
Not to mention...why was Sandra Ball-sac up there in the first place?! She was wildly under-qualified and wasn't doing anything that an astronaut couldn't do!

Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment:
*Spoilers*
Gravity, aka Hollywood's way of saying that I know more about the hazard of space, than a so called "trained astronaut". I practically predicted everything that these guys did horrifically wrong:
1) Matt (George Clooney) would have lived, if he weren't a cocky son of a bitch, that wanted to break that stupid "longest space walk" record, and if he didn't waste his fuel by flying laps around the space shuttle.¬†
2) When you hear that space debris is coming your way, you drop everything IMMEDIATELY!¬†
3) NASA could have predicted that there might be a debris chain reaction and would have called the mission off earlier. (also someone pointed out, that such a chain reaction is actually impossible)
4) I don't buy for a second that NASA couldn't establish ANY communication with the astronauts for the rest of the movie. A fucking Chinese bloke with a radio on Earth managed to contact Ryan (Sandra Bullock) in the Soyuz pod.
5) Ryan couldn't detach a harness that is made to be easy to handle. She stayed there like 2 minutes before detaching.
6) Any astronaut knows that oxygen is in short supply in space, and won't fucking have a panic attack every 5 minutes. An astronaut is trained to control their breathing.
7) Continuing the oxygen issue, you don't talk non-stop in space. Talking uses up more air. Matt knew Ryan had her tank low, yet he insisted she talked back to him.
8) These damn astronauts can't grab hold of anything if their life depended on it. Literally. Also those damn tethers break too easily.
9) There is a possibility that Matt could have lived if they both pulled fast and hard on that stupid tether. He would have definitely lived if he wasn't a cocky bastard earlier (see 1.)
10) Ryan takes a nice space stroll through the ISS (knowing full well that she is in danger). While doing this she didn't notice (or pay attention to) the electrical fire that was just starting. Also the fire alarm didn't detect fire, it only detected a fucking inferno. Fire is the most dangerous thing in space because oxygen saturation is a lot higher. Also without gravity, it's harder to control and it spreads faster. The fire detectors should detect a light candle, not wait till an out of control fire.
11) Ryan spend too much time on the intercom, trying to reach Matt or NASA, when it was already establish that Houston hasn't paid their phone bill.
12) Ryan doesn't know to brace herself before attempting to use a fire extinguisher in space. (At least she learned the hard way, and will use it properly later on).
13) NASA couldn't patch the software of the Soyuz to be able to use other languages (besides Russian) if necessary. It's the International Space Station. The only escape pods available should use a more international language. (i.e. English)
14) Ryan isn't careful enough with her tools. She almost lost that screwdriver while detaching the parachute off the Soyuz.
15) Ryan might be mentally challenged. She started howling like a wolf, to a Chinese bloke, instead of trying to save her ass. Also she is clearly depressed with suicidal tendencies. She probably wouldn't have gotten an OK from NASA. (Also hallucinating. But that could be because of the lack of oxygen).
16) Earlier Ryan proved she could stabilize the Soyuz pod, but when the Chinese Shenzou spirals out of control she does nothing. Autopilots are good, but that pod probably would have burned on re-entry in real life.¬†
17) Ryan didn't try to respond to NASA before exiting the pod. Also she should have taken the uniform off before exiting the pod. Or she could have tried keeping her helmet on. No smoke to get in her suit, she could have just waited there for the rescue. (unless the pod caught fire. In that case she would have bailed out).

So Hollywood, congrats on disappointing yet again.¬†

Comment: This movie was the biggest disappoint I've ever watched, and I didn't even have high expectations. Worse than Prometheus, worse than Avatar, on par with Elysium. I'm a big astrophysics fan and I work in a hospital lab; I was hooked about 10 minutes in. Then this film crashed and burned harder than the space station. Honestly, the CG and suspense was above average (I enjoyed it), but everything else was just brutal. The acting was mediocre at best; characters are all one-dimensional. The theme had much more potential. I cannot understand how people seriously think this movie is great. Even Transformers is more believable than this. I really hope Interstellar can make up for the bad taste this left. If someone rational could explain to me why this film is great, ie. Oscar-nod worthy, please do. I know you're going to say "allegory".

Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment:
Compared with what usually passes for "good" cinema these days, let alone Sci-fi, this film is pretty damn good.

Having said that, it's also quite a strange mix of cliches, action spectacle, introspective drama and thriller elements.

The action is indeed spectacular. And I think if Kubrick could've seen just how impressive the exterior space scenes look in this film, he might not have bothered with 2001: A Space Odyssey. He might have given up!

The thriller elements are also very successful, in the way that there is really no antagonist in the film. Well, not unless you count space itself, of course.
And there's a lot of excitement to be had with those damn oxygen tanks that always want to deplete at the worst possible moments.

In fact, I think "Oxygen" might have been a better title for the film.
Especially since the story has very little to do with gravity, and the crew's survival is utterly dependent on that precious O2.

The dramatic part is where I thought the film felt a bit underwhelming.
And this is in large part due to, what I consider, the miscasting of Sandra Bullock in the lead.
No no, she's not bad in the part. But showing emotion is not her greatest strength, and emotion is ultimately what's supposed to drive this entire film.

We, as the audience, are supposed to root for her. We're supposed to feel her frustration and anger, and empathize with her sense of hopelessness.
And we're meant to share her progress and setbacks. In other words, we should be with her on her journey to safety and some sort of personal redemption.

Unfortunately, that didn't happen for me. I found Sandra Bullock to be a little too stiff, and as a result, I didn't really relate enough to her to be fully engaged with the outcome.

The way I see it, it could have been almost ANYONE in that space suit, since I had so little emotional investment with the character. No matter who would be trying to survive this ordeal, it would of course be exciting to watch, but without the emotional involvement, it doesn't feel like a great loss if the worst happens, and therefor, the film has (sort of) failed as a drama.

I also didn't like the blatantly obvious religious overtones in the film.
There are references everywhere. Even when we're in the Chinese space station, we're "treated" to a huge closeup of a Buddha statuette.

Not to mention the return of "Angel George" at one crucial point.
Or how Sandra, who's playing a doctor (a scientist), after admitting that she doesn't know how to pray because she never needed to, suddenly has a change of heart in the face of danger, and now "talks to God".

I don't know, perhaps it's the Atheist in me that finds this hard to deal with.

And the worst line of the film is: "Half of North America just lost their Facebook".

SO? Facebook sucks! The loss of it would be good news!

All in all, though, the film does avoid the worst of the usual space cliches.
And when it doesn't, at least it weaves them into the story in a credible way, so that they don't distract us from what's important, unlike so many other films of this genre.

And even though I've been bitching a bit about it, Gravity is by far the best Sci-fi film I've seen since Danny Boyle's Sunshine.
Actually, Gravity is a much better film, and unlike Sunshine, it doesn't fuck up the ending.

Worth watching, people!

Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment:
Before I say anything else, I want to make it clear that Gravity is pretty unique, this is a singular and interesting movie
Don't worry, I'm not going to make spoilers. I'll just point out some aspects that are explained at the very beginning of the movie and some other that doesn't have much importance in the plot, so don't worry, you can keep reading safely.
¬†That said, I don't appreciate AT ALL how Russians are portrayed, they seem stupid and incompetent in the movie.
The idea of Russians disposing of satellites with missiles without having things under control is just absurd. I'm sick and tired of the obsolete Cold War drill of always blaming Russians for virtually anything, as if they were dumb, evil or something.
Russia has been one of the most competent, prepared, talented and successful countries regarding space exploration. Hell, they were the first to launch a satellite, a dog and a man to outer space. They have been admirable pioneers of space travel since 1957.
Now even American astronauts use the Russian Soyuz to get to the ISS, and they also learn Russian. If Russians were such fools, why the hell would Americans do this? It's easy, because Russians aren't fools, in fact they are pretty good at what they do.

A couple of other things:
1- When you grab a moving object (like a ship) in outer space, you end up moving exactly at the same speed, direction, rotation, etc. as the object itself.
It doesn't matter if you let go of it. As long as there's no pushing, pulling or acceleration, your movement and velocity will be exactly the same as that object's, you won't move away from it. If your ship is orbiting in space and you just let go of it, you'll keep your position relative to it for as long as neither of you accelerates. There's no moving away stuff, once you "get caught" by an object, you move exactly like it and your position relative to it is conserved. Pay atention to one particular scene with Clooney and you'll understand why I say this.¬†

2- Astronauts in the movie move too fast through space in relation to the rest of moving objects. It almost seems like they are actually on Earth's atmosphere sometimes, judging by the speed of their movement relative to the other things. In space there's no such thing as moving fast in relation to your ship when it's already orbiting and you just let go of it or push/pull yourself a bit...not unless one of you starts accelerating a lot. Maybe the ship can do this by burning its engines, but astronauts definitely can't get much acceleration using just their own muscles.

3-If you have an rcs system then you don't need to use the main engine in order to make the ship move. The "Reaction Control System" allows ships to maneuver in space, you can easily recognize it by its typical small thrusters that release white fumes every time they are activated. They don't provide much thrust, but they can make the ship move in pretty much any direction at low speeds.
¬†
4-If you don't know Chinese and you have no experience with the ship... Well, you'll understand when you see the movie.

I was going to say more, but I don't want to make spoilers, so I'll end here.
Gravity is like a modern version of Apollo 13 with more special effects, more dramatization and much less realism.

Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment:
Just saw "Gravity" and despite not living up to the incredible hype from the critics, it was a very good film.¬†

I would recommend that you make sure you see it in 3D at the Cinema (this coming from someone who hates 3D) as the 3-D in this film really does work and doesnt just have a 2D background with one part of the screen popping out at you. It immerses you fully into the film.¬†

Sure ive heard there are a few technical facts that are wrong and Cuaron admitted he knew about these but it was necessary for the sake of the medium of making a film. This isnt a NASA information video.

The film is not on the same level in terms of 2001 Space Odyssey in terms of depth, its a far more visceral film that needs to be experienced in the cinema.¬†
Id also say the first half of the film is excellent and the second half is solid but not as good.

There are still some metaphorical elements to the film revolving around sandra bullocks character and her reason for living or wanting to survive (I wont say any more as I will reveal spoilers.) Symbolism is included as well (fetal position and the end of the film etc)¬†

Comment:
Director Alfonso Cuaron summed up the film. I love this interpretation.¬†
"You have a character who's drifting into the void and is getting farther and farther away from human communication. It's a character that lives in her own bubble and is a victim of her own inertia. So it was a moment in which she has to come out of her own bubble and metaphorically shed her skin. She gets out of that suit and soon she's in her primordial state. The film deals with rebirth, and this is the first hint of that - the first moment that it's done visually in a more explicit way. This is a character who's been surrounded by death and, on the verge of it, finally finds peace and repose."¬†

Comment: Sound is just vibrations traveling through air. In empty space, there is no air. So objects crashing into each other will not cause any vibrations. However, if there is presence of gas, then it is possible since gasses can propogate sound waves. But if the gas cloud is not dense enough, it won't be able to create large enough waves that can travel any significant distance or impacts on our eardrums. A good sound recorder could I suppose. Comment: A shot that alludes to this is when she comes back inside the air lock from almost losing consciousness (due to lack of O2) and wraps herself up like a baby while floating inside the air lock. From then on she encounters lots of tribulations but continues to live after having the desire to and accepting where she is. I study film producing and one crucial part of it is finding a film's theme.

Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment: The theme in this is moving on with life and finding your "middle path", which is a big practice in the Buddhist teachings. The fact that she learned this alone in space from her daughter's death, with no hospitality for life and no sound, shows just why she was able to come out of that alive. She was accepting of what happened and moved on from it, and in turn was given more opportunities in life.

Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment: While an IMAX screens are important, few people seem to mention sound setups. This sound for Gravity was designed for Dolby ATMOS. Instead of a series of surround sound speakers one a single plane, ATMOS uses an array of speakers on the walls and ceiling. This allows for the an unbelievable aural perception of depth and scale, as the perceived origin point of sounds are moving around in three dimensions instead of two. You can search for theaters with Dolby ATMOS on Dolby's website.

Comment: To educate your dumb ass further, the force of gravity in LEO (low Earth orbit) is almost as strong as it is on the surface of the Earth. An object in any orbit around the Earth stays in orbit because it is moving laterally at a very high speed, and this velocity offsets the effect of gravity. If the object slows down, it immediately begins falling to Earth under the force of gravity. That's precisely how an orbiting spacecraft re-enters the atmosphere and returns to Earth, by slowing down.

Comment: Wrong.  Her body is also subject to centrifugal force generated by the rotation of the arm. Her actual trajectory would be the resultant of that vector and the translational (straight line) motion vector, so it would depend on when exactly she detached.

Comment: You almost had me going there, but actually what you say is not true. When strapped to the arm they are in effect one body rotating around a single center of gravity, but the mass as a whole is moving through space in a straight line.  Once she releases the strap she will continue to travel in a straight line in the direction she was traveling at the moment the connection is broken.  It would be against the laws of physics for her body to travel in the shape of an ellipse by her momentum alone.

Comment: The implausibility is much greater than that. It's a 3D issue, not a 2D one. Orbital paths also vary in their distance from (height above) the Earth. The Hubble telescope is in a much higher orbit than that of the space station. Orbiting debris impacting Hubble would thus remain far away from anything orbiting at the height of the space station. And it would be equally impossible for an astronaut orbiting at/near Hubble height to descend to space station height without the use of a spacecraft.

Comment:
Google "Kessler Syndrome" it's the situation this movie is based off of.
Basically, when something is on a very fast orbit, and it collides with something else, it has the potential to create even more debris which follows in the same orbit, causing a domino effect. 

In the movie, a trained astronaut and an inexperienced medical engineer on her first spacewalk must race against time as the debris hurdles around creating even more debris circa every 40 minutes.

Title: Gravity - Official Main Trailer [2K HD]
Comment: The Earth's atmosphere doesn't just stop at a certain distance from the Earth, it kind of fades away. The Earth's thermosphere starts at about 59 miles up, and ends roughly 420 miles up, it still contains molecules just very spread out. It's better to not think of them as actual layers, but a thinning as you go higher. The Earth's atmosphere doesn't really "end" it just gets fewer molecules the further you go up, and that distance is about ~10,000km (~6200 miles) up.
